Talking of the photo, taken last week, Stefan said: 'I used a whole day just planning to get this picture. The goal was to find a place far away from the castle, but with the setting comet above it.

'It was just a question of making sure I was in the right place at the right time.

'From this place, I used a really big telephoto lens to combine the castle as well as the comet in an appropriate size in one single image. Luckily there was no cloud, the comet and castle lit up beautifully and it all paid off.'

The comet is visible next to a crescent moon in the western sky after sunset over Maryland in the U.S.

The comet was first visible to amateur astronomers in May last year and by October they estimated the comet and trail was 75,000 miles long.

It was brightest to northern hemisphere observers around March 10 this year.

Once it rounds the sun its orbit will bring it back in 110,000 years. It is literally a once-in-a-lifetime comet.

